{"title_page": "Stuart Christie", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Anarchism sidebar}}\n'''Stuart Christie''' (born 10 July 1946) is a Scottish [[anarchist]] writer and publisher. When aged 18, Christie was arrested  while carrying explosives to assassinate the Spanish [[caudillo]], General  [[Francisco Franco]]. He was later alleged to be a member of the [[Angry Brigade]], but was acquitted of related charges. He went on to found the [[Cienfuegos Press]] publishing house and in 2008 the online Anarchist Film Channel, which hosts films and documentaries with anarchist and [[libertarian socialist]] themes.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nChristie was born in the [[Partick]] area of [[Glasgow]] and raised in [[Blantyre, South Lanarkshire|Blantyre]] by his mother and grandparents, becoming an anarchist at a young age. He ascribes this to his grandmother's influence, \"Basically, what she did was provide a moral barometer which married almost exactly with that of [[libertarian socialism]] and anarchism, and she provided the star which I followed.\"<ref name=Campbell>{{cite news |title=The woolly-jumpered anarchist |first=Duncan |last=Campbell |authorlink=Duncan Campbell (The Guardian) |url= https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/aug/23/spain.politics |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher= |location= |date=23 August 2004 |at=G2 p2 |accessdate= |ref= }}</ref> He joined the [[Anarchist Federation of Scotland|Anarchist Federation]] in Glasgow in 1962, at the age of 16. He became active in [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament|CND]] campaigns, attracted to the more militant approach of the [[Direct Action Committee]] and [[Committee of 100 (United Kingdom)|Committee of 100]] and took part in the confrontational [[Faslane Naval Base]] CND demonstration on 14 February 1963, among others.<ref>http://www.xmission.com/pub/lists/abolition-usa/archive/v01.n257</ref>\n\n===Attempt to assassinate Franco===\nOn the last day of July 1964, an 18-year-old Christie departed London for [[Paris]], where he picked up [[plastic explosives]] from the anarchist organisation [[Defensa Interior]].<ref name=\"Keeley\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/scotland/article3027528.ece|title=Anarchist jailed over plot to kill Franco fights to clear name|last=Keeley|first=Graham|date=21 May 2011|work=The Times|accessdate=21 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nBefore he left [[England]], he was interviewed for a television programme with [[Malcolm Muggeridge]], a known [[MI6]] contact, and asked whether he felt the assassination of Franco would be right.  He answered that it would; when the programme was broadcast after his arrest in Spain, these comments were edited out.\n\nChristie hitchhiked into Spain and was arrested in Madrid on 11 August 1964 in possession of explosives.  He faced a military trial and a possible execution sentence by [[garrote]], but was instead sentenced to twenty years in prison.  An accomplice, Fernando Carballo Blanco, was sentenced to thirty years' imprisonment.  He served three years in [[Carabanchel Prison]], where he studied for [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]]s and was brought into contact with anarchist prisoners, including [[Miguel Garc\u00eda Garc\u00eda]], [[Luis Andres Edo]] and [[Juan Busquets]].<ref name=Meltzer>{{cite book |title=I Couldn't Paint Golden Angels |last=Meltzer |first=Albert |authorlink=Albert Meltzer |year=1996 |publisher=AK Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=1-873176-93-7 |page=164 |chapter=IX: The Iberian Liberation Council; How the Thames was Lost |url=https://www.katesharpleylibrary.net/6djj4k }}</ref> Christie was later freed. The official reason given by [[Francoist Spain]] was that it was due to a plea from Christie's mother.<ref name=Meltzer />\n\n===Back in Britain===\n[[File:IWW picket Sydney June1981.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Industrial Workers of the World]] picket in Australia in 1981, calling for the release of Christie's wife Brenda from prison]]\nAfter his release he continued his activism in the [[Anarchism in the United Kingdom|British anarchist movement]], re-formed the [[Anarchist Black Cross]] and ''[[Black Flag (newspaper)|Black Flag]]'' with [[Albert Meltzer]], was acquitted of involvement with the Angry Brigade, and started the publishing house Cienfuegos Press, which for a number of years he operated from the remote island of [[Sanday, Orkney]], where he also edited and published a local Orcadian newspaper, ''The Free-Winged Eagle''.\n\nChristie has had various writing and journalistic jobs including as editor of an unauthorised British edition of ''[[Pravda]]'' and ''Argumenty i Fakty'' (''Arguments and Facts International'') in the late years of the [[Soviet Union]] and the early years of the Russian Federation.<ref name=Campbell />\n\n==Published work==\nAn updated and single-volume version of his autobiography ''Granny Made Me an Anarchist'' was published in 2004 by Scribner. It had previously been published in three parts, the other titles being ''General Franco Made Me a Terrorist'',<ref>[http://flag.blackened.net/revolt/anarchism/writers/anarcho/reviews/biography/christie2.html Review of ''General Franco made me a \"Terrorist\" - The Christie File: Part 2, 1964-1967''.]</ref> and ''Edward Heath Made Me Angry''.<ref>[http://news.infoshop.org/article.php?story=20050726231205920 Review of ''Edward Heath Made Me Angry''], Infoshop News, 27 July 2005.</ref> Christie attracted criticism from some fellow anarchists for making a [[gesture politics|gestural protest]] vote against [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and its war in [[Iraq]] by voting for [[George Galloway]]'s [[Respect - The Unity Coalition]] in the [[European Parliament]] elections that year.<ref name=Campbell /> Christie has written articles attacking [[freemasonry]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=https://www.katesharpleylibrary.net/51c5t6\n|title= A wink, a nod, or a shake of the hand: on the Masons\n|date= 13 July 1983\n|work= Kate Sharpley Library\n|page=  \n}}</ref>\n\nHe also wrote, with Meltzer, ''The Floodgates of Anarchy'', which includes an early version of the [[political compass]]. His other books include ''[[Stefano Delle Chiaie]]: Portrait of a Black Terrorist'',<ref>Stefano Delle Chiaie: Portrait of a Black Terrorist. London: Anarchy Magazine/Refract Publications, 1984. 182 pages ({{ISBN|0-946222-09-6}})</ref> (on Italian neo-fascist terrorist [[Stefano Delle Chiaie]], founder of ''[[National Vanguard (Italy)|Avanguardia Nazionale]]'' and member of [[Propaganda Due|P2]] masonic lodge) and ''We, the Anarchists! A study of the [[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|Iberian Anarchist Federation]] (FAI) 1927-1937'' (2000).<ref>[http://flag.blackened.net/revolt/spain/review_we_anarchists.html Review of ''We, the Anarchists! A study of the Iberian Anarchist Federation (FAI) 1927-1937''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412002305/http://flag.blackened.net/revolt/spain/review_we_anarchists.html |date=12 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAs a publisher Christie founded [[Cienfuegos Press]] in 1972 and edited the ''Cienfuegos Anarchist Review'' (c. 1977\u20131982), Refract Publications (1982), The Meltzer Press (1996) and Christiebooks/Christiebooks.com/Read 'N' Noir. He also edited ''[[The Hastings Trawler]]'', a monthly magazine that ran from 2005 to 2006.\n\nChristie also translated into English the biography of [[Francisco Sabate Llopart]], ''Sabate: An Extraordinary Guerrilla'', by [[Antonio T\u00e9llez|Antonio T\u00e9llez Sol\u00e1]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Colin Ward]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/ChristieStuart.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209203210/http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/ChristieStuart.htm|archivedate=2015-12-09|title=Stuart Christie|publisher=Daily Bleed|work=Anarchist Encyclopedia}}\n*[http://libcom.org/library/franco-assassination-attempt-stuart-christie 1964: Stuart Christie's account of his actions in a Franco assassination attempt]\n* {{Cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Duncan |title=A revolution in cinema? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2006-11-24 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/24/1 |issn=0261-3077 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130918050022/http://www.christiebooks.com/ChristieBooksWP/ ChristieBooks and Anarchist Film Channel, Radio etc.]\n*\"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/aug/23/spain.bookextracts 'My stomach churned. Something had gone badly wrong ... ']\", an edited extract from ''[[Granny Made Me an Anarchist]]'', by Stuart Christie. ''Guardian.co.uk'' Guardian News and Media Limited. 23 August 2004.\n;Interviews\n*\"[http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/looking-back-at-anger/  Looking Back at Anger]\", Stuart Christie interview with Andrew Stevens. ''3:AM Magazine''. 2004.\n* [http://www.koletmag.se/2011/03/stuart-christie/ Den skotske bombmannen] Stuart Christie interview with Jonas St\u00e5l in the Swedish magazine ''Kolet'', 2011.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Christie, Stuart}}\n<!--CATEGORIES-->\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Partick]]\n[[Category:Historians of anarchism]]\n[[Category:Anarchist writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish anarchists]]\n[[Category:Scottish autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Scottish publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Scottish translators]]\n[[Category:Scottish people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Anarchism in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Anarchism sidebar}}\n'''Stuart Christie''' (born 10 July 1946) is a Scottish [[anarchist]] writer and publisher. When aged 18, Christie was arrested  while carrying explosives to assassinate the Spanish [[caudillo]], General  [[Francisco Franco]]. He was later alleged to be a member of the [[Angry Brigade]], but was acquitted of related charges. He went on to found the [[Cienfuegos Press]] publishing house and in 2008 the online [[Anarchist Film Channel]], which hosts films and documentaries with anarchist and [[libertarian socialist]] themes.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nChristie was born in the [[Partick]] area of [[Glasgow]] and raised in [[Blantyre, South Lanarkshire|Blantyre]] by his mother and grandparents, becoming an anarchist at a young age. He ascribes this to his grandmother's influence, \"Basically, what she did was provide a moral barometer which married almost exactly with that of [[libertarian socialism]] and anarchism, and she provided the star which I followed.\"<ref name=Campbell>{{cite news |title=The woolly-jumpered anarchist |first=Duncan |last=Campbell |authorlink=Duncan Campbell (The Guardian) |url= https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/aug/23/spain.politics |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher= |location= |date=23 August 2004 |at=G2 p2 |accessdate= |ref= }}</ref> He joined the [[Anarchist Federation of Scotland|Anarchist Federation]] in Glasgow in 1962, at the age of 16. He became active in [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament|CND]] campaigns, attracted to the more militant approach of the [[Direct Action Committee]] and [[Committee of 100 (United Kingdom)|Committee of 100]] and took part in the confrontational [[Faslane Naval Base]] CND demonstration on 14 February 1963, among others.<ref>http://www.xmission.com/pub/lists/abolition-usa/archive/v01.n257</ref>\n\n===Attempt to assassinate Franco===\nOn the last day of July 1964, an 18-year-old Christie departed London for [[Paris]], where he picked up [[plastic explosives]] from the anarchist organisation [[Defensa Interior]].<ref name=\"Keeley\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/scotland/article3027528.ece|title=Anarchist jailed over plot to kill Franco fights to clear name|last=Keeley|first=Graham|date=21 May 2011|work=The Times|accessdate=21 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nBefore he left [[England]], he was interviewed for a television programme with [[Malcolm Muggeridge]], a known [[MI6]] contact, and asked whether he felt the assassination of Franco would be right.  He answered that it would; when the programme was broadcast after his arrest in Spain, these comments were edited out.\n\nChristie hitchhiked into Spain and was arrested in Madrid on 11 August 1964 in possession of explosives.  He faced a military trial and a possible execution sentence by [[garrote]], but was instead sentenced to twenty years in prison.  An accomplice, Fernando Carballo Blanco, was sentenced to thirty years' imprisonment.  He served three years in [[Carabanchel Prison]], where he studied for [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]]s and was brought into contact with anarchist prisoners, including [[Miguel Garc\u00eda Garc\u00eda]], [[Luis Andres Edo]] and [[Juan Busquets]].<ref name=Meltzer>{{cite book |title=I Couldn't Paint Golden Angels |last=Meltzer |first=Albert |authorlink=Albert Meltzer |year=1996 |publisher=AK Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=1-873176-93-7 |page=164 |chapter=IX: The Iberian Liberation Council; How the Thames was Lost |url=https://www.katesharpleylibrary.net/6djj4k }}</ref> Christie was later freed. The official reason given by [[Francoist Spain]] was that it was due to a plea from Christie's mother.<ref name=Meltzer />\n\n===Back in Britain===\n[[File:IWW picket Sydney June1981.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Industrial Workers of the World]] picket in Australia in 1981, calling for the release of Christie's wife Brenda from prison]]\nAfter his release he continued his activism in the [[Anarchism in the United Kingdom|British anarchist movement]], re-formed the [[Anarchist Black Cross]] and ''[[Black Flag (newspaper)|Black Flag]]'' with [[Albert Meltzer]], was acquitted of involvement with the Angry Brigade, and started the publishing house Cienfuegos Press, which for a number of years he operated from the remote island of [[Sanday, Orkney]], where he also edited and published a local Orcadian newspaper, ''The Free-Winged Eagle''.\n\nChristie has had various writing and journalistic jobs including as editor of an unauthorised British edition of ''[[Pravda]]'' and ''Argumenty i Fakty'' (''Arguments and Facts International'') in the late years of the [[Soviet Union]] and the early years of the Russian Federation.<ref name=Campbell />\n\n==Published work==\nAn updated and single-volume version of his autobiography ''Granny Made Me an Anarchist'' was published in 2004 by Scribner. It had previously been published in three parts, the other titles being ''General Franco Made Me a Terrorist'',<ref>[http://flag.blackened.net/revolt/anarchism/writers/anarcho/reviews/biography/christie2.html Review of ''General Franco made me a \"Terrorist\" - The Christie File: Part 2, 1964-1967''.]</ref> and ''Edward Heath Made Me Angry''.<ref>[http://news.infoshop.org/article.php?story=20050726231205920 Review of ''Edward Heath Made Me Angry''], Infoshop News, 27 July 2005.</ref> Christie attracted criticism from some fellow anarchists for making a [[gesture politics|gestural protest]] vote against [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and its war in [[Iraq]] by voting for [[George Galloway]]'s [[Respect - The Unity Coalition]] in the [[European Parliament]] elections that year.<ref name=Campbell /> Christie has written articles attacking [[freemasonry]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=https://www.katesharpleylibrary.net/51c5t6\n|title= A wink, a nod, or a shake of the hand: on the Masons\n|date= 13 July 1983\n|work= Kate Sharpley Library\n|page=  \n}}</ref>\n\nHe also wrote, with Meltzer, ''The Floodgates of Anarchy'', which includes an early version of the [[political compass]]. His other books include ''[[Stefano Delle Chiaie]]: Portrait of a Black Terrorist'',<ref>Stefano Delle Chiaie: Portrait of a Black Terrorist. London: Anarchy Magazine/Refract Publications, 1984. 182 pages ({{ISBN|0-946222-09-6}})</ref> (on Italian neo-fascist terrorist [[Stefano Delle Chiaie]], founder of ''[[National Vanguard (Italy)|Avanguardia Nazionale]]'' and member of [[Propaganda Due|P2]] masonic lodge) and ''We, the Anarchists! A study of the [[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|Iberian Anarchist Federation]] (FAI) 1927-1937'' (2000).<ref>[http://flag.blackened.net/revolt/spain/review_we_anarchists.html Review of ''We, the Anarchists! A study of the Iberian Anarchist Federation (FAI) 1927-1937''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412002305/http://flag.blackened.net/revolt/spain/review_we_anarchists.html |date=12 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAs a publisher Christie founded [[Cienfuegos Press]] in 1972 and edited the ''Cienfuegos Anarchist Review'' (c. 1977\u20131982), Refract Publications (1982), The Meltzer Press (1996) and Christiebooks/Christiebooks.com/Read 'N' Noir. He also edited ''[[The Hastings Trawler]]'', a monthly magazine that ran from 2005 to 2006.\n\nChristie also translated into English the biography of [[Francisco Sabate Llopart]], ''Sabate: An Extraordinary Guerrilla'', by [[Antonio T\u00e9llez|Antonio T\u00e9llez Sol\u00e1]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Colin Ward]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/ChristieStuart.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209203210/http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/ChristieStuart.htm|archivedate=2015-12-09|title=Stuart Christie|publisher=Daily Bleed|work=Anarchist Encyclopedia}}\n*[http://libcom.org/library/franco-assassination-attempt-stuart-christie 1964: Stuart Christie's account of his actions in a Franco assassination attempt]\n* {{Cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Duncan |title=A revolution in cinema? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2006-11-24 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/24/1 |issn=0261-3077 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130918050022/http://www.christiebooks.com/ChristieBooksWP/ ChristieBooks and Anarchist Film Channel, Radio etc.]\n*\"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/aug/23/spain.bookextracts 'My stomach churned. Something had gone badly wrong ... ']\", an edited extract from ''[[Granny Made Me an Anarchist]]'', by Stuart Christie. ''Guardian.co.uk'' Guardian News and Media Limited. 23 August 2004.\n;Interviews\n*\"[http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/looking-back-at-anger/  Looking Back at Anger]\", Stuart Christie interview with Andrew Stevens. ''3:AM Magazine''. 2004.\n* [http://www.koletmag.se/2011/03/stuart-christie/ Den skotske bombmannen] Stuart Christie interview with Jonas St\u00e5l in the Swedish magazine ''Kolet'', 2011.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Christie, Stuart}}\n<!--CATEGORIES-->\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Partick]]\n[[Category:Historians of anarchism]]\n[[Category:Anarchist writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish anarchists]]\n[[Category:Scottish autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Scottish publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Scottish translators]]\n[[Category:Scottish people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Anarchism in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Konli17", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_Christie"}
{"title_page": "Sandusky Mall", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{infobox shopping mall\n| name = The Sandusky Mall\n| image = \n| caption = \n| location = [[Perkins Township, Erie County, Ohio|Perkins Township, Ohio]] \n(Suburb Of Sandusky, Ohio)\n| opening_date = 1977<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=mNsbAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Sandusky+Mall,+Sandusky,+OH+656,206+sq.+ft+Montgomery+Ward,+Sears%22&dq=%22Sandusky+Mall,+Sandusky,+OH+656,206+sq.+ft+Montgomery+Ward,+Sears%22&source=bl&ots=ZckwbCIyrM&sig=uxuBIiNZUFUM_RsVoSWJhp8xVRU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=4JBSULq5LZC49gSPsYHQBA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAA</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.4183333|-82.6691667|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-OH}}\n| developer = [[Cafaro Company]]\n| manager = Cafaro Company\n| owner = Cafaro Company\n| number_of_stores = 70+\n| number_of_anchors = 4 (2 occupied, 2 vacant)\nAnchors: JCPenney, Hobby Lobby\n\nSub-Anchors: Books-A-Million, TJMaxx\n| floor_area = \n| floors = 1 (2 in Former Macy\u2019s)\n| publictransit = Sandusky Transit System (STS)\n| website = {{url|sandusky-mall.com}}\n}}\n'''Sandusky Mall''' is an indoor [[shopping center]] located in [[Perkins Township, Erie County, Ohio|Perkins Township]], south of [[Sandusky, Ohio]].  It is located on the east side of [[US Route 250|US 250]] (Milan Road), north of [[Interstate 80 in Ohio|I-80]]/[[Interstate 90 in Ohio|I-90]] ([[Ohio Turnpike]]) and [[Ohio State Route 2|SR 2]]. It is the only major shopping center within 45 miles. The mall comprises more than 70 stores including two [[anchor stores|anchor stores,]] [[JCPenney]], and Hobby Lobby. The mall has two sub anchors, Books-A-Million, and TJ Maxx. There are two vacant anchors currently last occupied by [[Macy's]], and [[Elder-Beerman]]. JCPenney had previously operated a store in downtown Sandusky.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sA0QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=josDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6016,3588791&dq=sandusky-mall&hl=en|title=Ohio town feels effect of new mall|last=Giegerich|first=Steve|work=[[The Free-Lance Star]]|accessdate=August 10, 2010}}</ref> It is managed by [[Cafaro Company]] of [[Youngstown, Ohio]].\n\n==History==\nMall construction began in 1976 and Sandusky Mall opened in 1977. Its original anchors included [[JCPenney]], [[Elder-Beerman]], [[The May Department Stores Company]] (simply the May Co.), and [[Montgomery Ward]] (later [[Sears]] in 1986). The outdoor section, [[Child World]] closed in 1992 and later converted to [[OfficeMax]] in 1994, then closed in 2005. It was converted to K&K Home Furnishings in 2006, then closed in 2014. It later converted to a Planet Fitness in 2015.\n\nThe May Co. rebranded their store at the Sandusky Mall as [[Kaufmann's]] in the mid-1990s. In 2006, the store was converted to [[Macy's]], when May Department Stores Company and Federated Department Stores merged into Macy's, Inc. [[Borders Group|Borders]] opened in 2005.  [[T. J. Maxx|TJ Maxx]] was added in 2009. Borders closed in 2011. A few months later, it was replaced by [[Books-A-Million|BAM!]].\n\nOn April 7, 2016, Sears announced that its store would be closing in June 2016.<ref>http://www.sanduskyregister.com/story/201701040044</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2017, Macy's announced that its store would also be closing as part of a plan to close 100 stores nationwide over the next several years. The store closed in March 2017.<ref>http://www.sanduskyregister.com/story/201701040044</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2018, it was announced that Elder-Beerman would be closing all of their stores after the parent company, Bon-Ton became bankrupt. The store closed late August 2018. \n\nIn December 2018, Cafaro Company announced that they had a redevelopment plan set in place for the mall with chances on the horizon coming within the next year. \n[[File:Sandusky Mall Viewed From Back of Nearby Mcdonald's Lot.jpg|thumb|445x445px|Picture of the mall taken by YouTuber, \"Tom's Terrific Retales\"]]\nOn June 30, 2019, It was announced that Hobby Lobby, a crafts/ home decor store would be coming to the Sandusky Mall. They will replace the former Sears store. It opened March 23rd, 2020.  \n\nThe mall is being transformed into a mix-used property to feature residential, entertainment, and even office space. Changes are currently underway. \n\nThe mall features Tenants such as JCPenney, Hobby Lobby, BAM!, TJMaxx, American Eagle, Bath and Body Works, Victorias Secret, Kay Jewelers, Journeys, Spencers, Aeropostale, GNC, Lids, Express Factory, Zales Jewelers, Hot Topic, Finish Line, Shoe Department Encore, Christopher & Banks, and more.\n\nThe malls Food Court offers Asian Express, Auntie Anne's, Mrs. Fields, and Cheers Sports Bar & Grill. The Food Court is located in the west corridor, or can be accessed through the main entrance outside. The mall also has a coffee shop located in Books-A-Million. Restaurants located on the mall property outside of the mall itself include: Cracker Barrel, Red Lobster, and Texas Roadhouse. <br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cleveland malls}}\n{{Shopping malls in Ohio}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1977]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Cafaro Company]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Erie County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Erie County, Ohio]]\n\n\n{{US-mall-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{infobox shopping mall\n| name = The Sandusky Mall\n| image = \n| caption = \n| location = [[Perkins Township, Erie County, Ohio|Perkins Township, Ohio]] \n(Suburb Of Sandusky, Ohio)\n| opening_date = 1977<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=mNsbAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Sandusky+Mall,+Sandusky,+OH+656,206+sq.+ft+Montgomery+Ward,+Sears%22&dq=%22Sandusky+Mall,+Sandusky,+OH+656,206+sq.+ft+Montgomery+Ward,+Sears%22&source=bl&ots=ZckwbCIyrM&sig=uxuBIiNZUFUM_RsVoSWJhp8xVRU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=4JBSULq5LZC49gSPsYHQBA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAA</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.4183333|-82.6691667|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-OH}}\n| developer = [[Cafaro Company]]\n| manager = Cafaro Company\n| owner = Cafaro Company\n| number_of_stores = 70+\n| number_of_anchors = 4 (2 occupied, 2 vacant)\nAnchors: JCPenney, Hobby Lobby\n\nSub-Anchors: Books-A-Million, TJMaxx\n| floor_area = \n| floors = 1 (2 in Former Macy\u2019s)\n| publictransit = Sandusky Transit System (STS)\n| website = {{url|sandusky-mall.com}}\n}}\n'''Sandusky Mall''' is an indoor [[shopping center]] located in [[Perkins Township, Erie County, Ohio|Perkins Township]], south of [[Sandusky, Ohio]].  It is located on the east side of [[US Route 250|US 250]] (Milan Road), north of [[Interstate 80 in Ohio|I-80]]/[[Interstate 90 in Ohio|I-90]] ([[Ohio Turnpike]]) and [[Ohio State Route 2|SR 2]]. It is the only major shopping center within 45 miles. The mall comprises more than 70 stores including two [[anchor stores|anchor stores,]] [[JCPenney]], and Hobby Lobby. The mall has two sub anchors, Books-A-Million, and TJ Maxx. There are two vacant anchors currently last occupied by [[Macy's]], and [[Elder-Beerman]]. JCPenney had previously operated a store in downtown Sandusky.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sA0QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=josDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6016,3588791&dq=sandusky-mall&hl=en|title=Ohio town feels effect of new mall|last=Giegerich|first=Steve|work=[[The Free-Lance Star]]|accessdate=August 10, 2010}}</ref> It is managed by [[Cafaro Company]] of [[Youngstown, Ohio]].\n\n==History==\nMall construction began in 1976 and Sandusky Mall opened in 1977. Its original anchors included [[JCPenney]], [[Elder-Beerman]], [[The May Department Stores Company]] (simply the May Co.), and [[Montgomery Ward]] (later [[Sears]] in 1986). The outdoor section, [[Child World]] closed in 1992 and later converted to [[OfficeMax]] in 1994, then closed in 2005. It was converted to K&K Home Furnishings in 2006, then closed in 2014. It later converted to a Planet Fitness in 2015.\n\nThe May Co. rebranded their store at the Sandusky Mall as [[Kaufmann's]] in the mid-1990s. In 2006, the store was converted to [[Macy's]], when May Department Stores Company and Federated Department Stores merged into Macy's, Inc. [[Borders Group|Borders]] opened in 2005.  [[T. J. Maxx|TJ Maxx]] was added in 2009. Borders closed in 2011. A few months later, it was replaced by [[Books-A-Million|BAM!]].\n\nOn April 7, 2016, Sears announced that its store would be closing in June 2016.<ref>http://www.sanduskyregister.com/story/201701040044</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2017, Macy's announced that its store would also be closing as part of a plan to close 100 stores nationwide over the next several years. The store closed in March 2017.<ref>http://www.sanduskyregister.com/story/201701040044</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2018, it was announced that Elder-Beerman would be closing all of their stores after the parent company, Bon-Ton became bankrupt. The store closed late August 2018. \n\nIn December 2018, Cafaro Company announced that they had a redevelopment plan set in place for the mall with chances on the horizon coming within the next year. \n[[File:Sandusky Mall Viewed From Back of Nearby Mcdonald's Lot.jpg|thumb|445x445px|Picture of the mall taken by YouTuber, \"Tom's Terrific Retales\"]]\nOn June 30, 2019, It was announced that Hobby Lobby, a crafts/ home decor store would be coming to the Sandusky Mall. They will replace the former Sears store. It opened March 23rd, 2020.  \n\nThe mall is being transformed into a mix-used property to feature residential, entertainment, and even office space. Changes are currently underway. \n\nThe mall features Tenants such as JCPenney, Hobby Lobby, BAM!, TJMaxx, American Eagle, Bath and Body Works, Victorias Secret, Kay Jewelers, Journeys, Spencers, Aeropostale, GNC, Lids, Express Factory, Zales Jewelers, Hot Topic, Finish Line, Shoe Department Encore, Christopher & Banks, and more.\n\nThe malls Food Court offers Asian Express, Auntie Anne's, Lotus Garden, Mrs. Fields, and Cheers Sports Bar & Grill. The Food Court is located in the west corridor, or can be accessed through the main entrance outside. The mall also has a coffee shop located in Books-A-Million. Restaurants located on the mall property outside of the mall itself include: Cracker Barrel, Red Lobster, and Texas Roadhouse. <br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cleveland malls}}\n{{Shopping malls in Ohio}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1977]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Cafaro Company]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Erie County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Erie County, Ohio]]\n\n\n{{US-mall-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ski457", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandusky_Mall"}
{"title_page": "London Underground 1959 Stock", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox train\n|name         = 1959 Stock\n|image        = File:Braye Road Stn.JPG\n|image_size   = 258px\n|caption      = Two cars of 1959 stock as preserved on the [[Alderney Railway]]\n|manufacturer = [[Metro-Cammell]]\n|service      = 1959\u20132000\n|family       =\n|replaced     =\n|lines        =\n|carlength    = DM {{convert|52|ft|2+5/16|in|m|sigfig=4|abbr=on}}<br>NDM {{convert|51|ft|2+13/16|in|m|sigfig=4|abbr=on}}<br>T {{convert|51|ft|2+13/16|in|m|sigfig=4|abbr=on}}\n|trainlength  =\n|width        = {{convert|8|ft|6+1/4|in|m|sigfig=4|abbr=on}}\n|height       = {{convert|9|ft|5+1/2|in|m|sigfig=4|abbr=on}}\n|maxspeed     =\n|weight       = DM {{convert|26.62|LT|t ST}}<br>NDM {{convert|24.28|LT|t ST}}<br>T {{convert|20.67|LT|t ST}}\n|seating      = DM/NDM/T 40\n|stocktype    = [[London Underground infrastructure#Subsurface versus deep-level tube lines|Deep-level tube]]\n|notes        = {{Portal-inline|size=tiny|London transport}}\n}}\n[[File:Barons Court Station - geograph.org.uk - 1762897.jpg|thumb|1959 Stock train at {{LUL stations |station=Barons Court}}]]\nThe '''1959 Tube Stock''' was a type of [[London Underground]] tube train constructed in the late 1950s. They were intended for use on the [[Piccadilly line]], but also saw use on several other tube lines. It was the first production (not prototype) tube stock to have unpainted [[aluminium]] alloy bodywork.\n\n==Construction==\nThe 1959 Stock was built by [[Metro-Cammell]] in [[Birmingham]] and were closely based on the prototype aluminium alloy bodied [[London Underground 1956 Stock|1956 Stock]]. It operated at various times on the [[Northern line]], [[Bakerloo line]], [[Central line (London Underground)|Central line]] and Piccadilly line. The units had a long career, with some examples remaining in service until 2000, three years beyond their intended withdrawal date.\n\nThe 1959 Stock entered service on the Piccadilly line, but most units were drafted to the Central line because that line's [[London Underground Standard Stock|\"Standard stock\"]] was becoming very unreliable. The Central line's version of the 1959 stock, the [[London Underground 1962 Stock|1962 stock]], later took over.\n\n==Transfer from the Piccadilly line==\nThe Piccadilly line extension to [[Heathrow]], which opened in the early 1970s, coincided with the introduction of new [[London Underground 1973 Stock|1973 Stock]]. Therefore, the 1959 Stock was transferred to the Northern line between 1975 and 1979, allowing the scrapping of the oldest 1938 Stock on that line. The 1959 Stock also saw service on the Bakerloo line in the 1980s, again to facilitate withdrawal of 1938 Stock.\n\nWhen new, the 1959 stock was seen as distinctive because of the clean 'silver' exterior. Over the years, however, the trains' unpainted exteriors became jaded and dirty. The blue and grey interiors dated quickly. Stylistically the 1959 stock looked worn, but without the aesthetic red and green charm or old-fashioned thirties ambience of the more celebrated [[London Underground 1938 Stock|1938 stock]].\n\nBy the mid-1990s these units were getting old and were in need of works attention. By this time, all the remaining 1959 Stock was concentrated on the Northern line. Minor refurbishment of the stock took place, painting the blue/grey interiors white and replacing some of the seat moquettes. This was done in a haphazard manner, the white interiors becoming very dirty inside by 1998, and with a failure rate that had risen to 1 in {{convert|1864|mi|km|abbr=off}}, the 1959 Stock was in urgent need of replacement.\n\n==Replacement==\nNew trains in the form of [[London Underground 1995 Stock|1995 Stock]] were built as replacements for both the 1959 stock and the 30 trains of [[London Underground 1972 Stock|1972 stock]] also operating on the Northern line. Originally it had been planned to keep the 1972 stock running with the new trains, with the same extensive refurbishment as done to the 1972 stock on the Bakerloo line, but after one trial refurbishment of a Northern line 1972 stock carriage it was decided that it would be more cost-effective in the long run to have the line operated by one type of train only. Withdrawal of the 1959 Stock was a drawn-out affair, and when the last example was withdrawn on 28 January 2000, it was the only remaining tube train to be crewed with a motorman and a guard. One unit was repainted in \"heritage\" red and cream livery in 1990 to commemorate the line's 100th anniversary. One trailer forms part of the Central Line Sandite train, the other cars were 1962 stock.\n\nSeveral vehicles have been preserved, at various locations, including one complete 4-car unit (1304). The complete list is shown below.\n{|\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=45|DM\n!width=45|T\n!width=45|NDM\n!width=45|DM\n!Location\n|-\n|align=center|1018\n|align=center|2018\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|1304\n|Privately owned, [[Shaftesbury]], [[Dorset]]\n|-\n|align=center|1030\n|align=center|2044\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|[[Mangapps Railway Museum]]\n|-\n|align=center|1031\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|[[Epping Ongar Railway]]\n|-\n|align=center|1044\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|1045\n|[[Alderney Railway]]\n|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|2304\n|align=center|9305\n|align=center|-\n|Privately owned, [[Dinton, Wiltshire]]\n|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|1305\n|Sutton Hall Railway, [[Shopland]] Nr [[Rochford]], [[Essex]]\n|-\n|align=center|1306\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|Police Training School, [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]]\n|-\n|}\n|colspan=15 valign=\"top\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Key\n|-\n!DM\n|Driving motor\n|-\n!T\n|Trailer\n|-\n!NDM\n|Non-driving motor\n|}\n|}\n\n==External links==\n* 